<!-- S8: GLOSSARY -->
<section class="hidden" id="s8">
<div class="section-label">08 · REFERENCE</div>
<div class="section-title">Spectral Lexicon</div>
<div class="gloss-grid">
<div class="gloss-item"><div class="gloss-term">FFT (Fast Fourier Transform)</div><div class="gloss-def">Algorithm computing the Discrete Fourier Transform in O(N log N) time. Converts N time-domain samples into N/2 complex frequency-domain bins, each representing amplitude and phase at a specific frequency.</div></div>
<div class="gloss-item"><div class="gloss-term">Spectral Freeze</div><div class="gloss-def">Capturing a single FFT frame and continuously resynthesising it. Creates sustained, pitch-stable drones from any transient moment. Implemented in Max/MSP pfft~, Ableton Grain Delay, Paul's Extreme Stretch.</div></div>
<div class="gloss-item"><div class="gloss-term">Phase Vocoder</div><div class="gloss-def">Analysis/resynthesis system tracking instantaneous frequency via phase differences between overlapping FFT frames. Enables independent time and pitch manipulation — the basis of modern audio timestretching algorithms.</div></div>
<div class="gloss-item"><div class="gloss-term">Short-Time Fourier Transform</div><div class="gloss-def">FFT applied to windowed segments of a signal, producing a time-frequency representation (spectrogram). The window size determines frequency vs. time resolution — a fundamental tradeoff governed by the Heisenberg uncertainty principle.</div></div>
<div class="gloss-item"><div class="gloss-term">Convolution</div><div class="gloss-def">Mathematical operation multiplying two signals' frequency spectra. In audio: stamps the impulse response of any acoustic space onto a source signal, creating reverberation that perfectly emulates that environment.</div></div>
<div class="gloss-item"><div class="gloss-term">Impulse Response</div><div class="gloss-def">The response of a system to a Dirac impulse (infinitely short, infinitely loud click). Captures the complete acoustic character of a space or device. Convolved with any audio to impose that character.</div></div>
<div class="gloss-item"><div class="gloss-term">Spectral Morphing</div><div class="gloss-def">Interpolating between the spectral envelopes of two sounds, gradually transitioning timbre from one to the other. Creates hybrid timbres impossible to achieve through synthesis alone.</div></div>
<div class="gloss-item"><div class="gloss-term">Cross-Synthesis</div><div class="gloss-def">Using the spectral envelope of one sound to filter another — the frequency character of a vowel imposed on a string quartet, thunder's spectral shape stamped onto a piano chord.</div></div>
<div class="gloss-item"><div class="gloss-term">Window Function</div><div class="gloss-def">Taper applied to each FFT frame to reduce spectral leakage. Hann (cosine bell), Hamming, Blackman, and Kaiser windows trade main-lobe width against side-lobe suppression.</div></div>
<div class="gloss-item"><div class="gloss-term">Spectral Leakage</div><div class="gloss-def">Energy from one frequency bin appearing in adjacent bins due to non-integer periods within the FFT window. Minimised by windowing functions at the cost of frequency resolution.</div></div>
<div class="gloss-item"><div class="gloss-term">Bin</div><div class="gloss-def">A single frequency-domain sample output by an FFT. An N-point FFT produces N/2 bins, each representing a frequency range of (sample_rate / N) Hz. Bin width determines frequency resolution.</div></div>
<div class="gloss-item"><div class="gloss-term">Overlap-Add (OLA)</div><div class="gloss-def">Method for time-domain reconstruction from overlapping STFT frames. Modified frames are added with the correct overlap to produce continuous output. The basis of spectral processing and resynthesis.</div></div>
<div class="gloss-item"><div class="gloss-term">Spectral Subtraction</div><div class="gloss-def">Noise reduction technique estimating noise spectrum from a silent frame and subtracting it from subsequent frames in the frequency domain. Creates characteristic artefacts (musical noise) when pushed aggressively.</div></div>
<div class="gloss-item"><div class="gloss-term">Formant</div><div class="gloss-def">Resonant peak in a spectral envelope, primarily associated with vowel sounds in voice. Formant shifting independently from pitch is a key application of phase vocoder technology — voice character without pitch change.</div></div>
<div class="gloss-item"><div class="gloss-term">Partial</div><div class="gloss-def">An individual sinusoidal component in a complex sound. Harmonic partials have frequencies that are integer multiples of the fundamental; inharmonic partials create bell-like, metallic, or noisy timbres.</div></div>
<div class="gloss-item"><div class="gloss-term">Resynthesis</div><div class="gloss-def">Reconstructing a time-domain signal from spectral analysis data. Allows independent manipulation of amplitude, phase, and frequency of individual partials before reconstruction — additive synthesis from analysis.</div></div>
<div class="gloss-item"><div class="gloss-term">Spectral Centroid</div><div class="gloss-def">The weighted mean frequency of a spectrum — the "centre of mass." Perceptually correlates with brightness. High spectral centroid = bright sound; low = dark, dull. Fundamental audio feature for classification.</div></div>
<div class="gloss-item"><div class="gloss-term">Spectrogram</div><div class="gloss-def">2D representation of spectral content over time: x-axis = time, y-axis = frequency, pixel brightness = amplitude. The primary visual representation of audio in spectral editors (iZotope RX, Spectral Layers).</div></div>
<div class="gloss-item"><div class="gloss-term">Pitch Detection</div><div class="gloss-def">Estimating the fundamental frequency of a pitched sound from its spectrum — either via autocorrelation (YIN algorithm), cepstrum analysis, or machine learning models trained on labelled pitch data.</div></div>
<div class="gloss-item"><div class="gloss-term">Cepstrum</div><div class="gloss-def">The Inverse FFT of the log magnitude spectrum. The quefrency peak indicates the fundamental period of a pitched signal. Used for pitch detection, formant analysis, and echo removal algorithms.</div></div>
<div class="gloss-item"><div class="gloss-term">Mel Spectrogram</div><div class="gloss-def">Spectrogram with frequency axis warped to the Mel scale — perceptually uniform frequency spacing. The primary input representation for most deep learning audio models (speech recognition, music classification).</div></div>
<div class="gloss-item"><div class="gloss-term">MFCC</div><div class="gloss-def">Mel-Frequency Cepstral Coefficients — compact spectral shape representation derived from the Mel spectrogram's cepstrum. Standard feature set for speech recognition, timbre classification, and audio ML since the 1980s.</div></div>
</div>
</section>
<script>
const lerp=(a,b,t)=>a+(b-a)*t;
const clamp=(v,lo,hi)=>Math.max(lo,Math.min(hi,v));
const rand=(lo=0,hi=1)=>lo+Math.random()*(hi-lo);
function noise21(x,y){const ix=Math.floor(x),iy=Math.floor(y);const fx=x-ix,fy=y-iy;const ux=fx*fx*(3-2*fx),uy=fy*fy*(3-2*fy);const h=(a,b)=>{let n=(a*1619+b*31337)^(a*31337);n=(n>>8)^n;return(n&0xffff)/65535;};return lerp(lerp(h(ix,iy),h(ix+1,iy),ux),lerp(h(ix,iy+1),h(ix+1,iy+1),ux),uy);}
function fbm(x,y,oct=4){let v=0,a=0.5,f=1;for(let i=0;i<oct;i++){v+=a*noise21(x*f,y*f);a*=0.5;f*=2.1;}return v;}

class LagFilter{constructor(init,tau){this.value=init;this.tau=tau;}update(target,dt){const k=1-Math.exp(-dt/this.tau);this.value+=k*(target-this.value);return this.value;}}
const lagHMX=new LagFilter(0.5,0.9);
const lagHMY=new LagFilter(0.5,0.9);
const lagHPulse=new LagFilter(0,0.2);
const lagFund=new LagFilter(220,0.4);
const lagHarm=new LagFilter(6,0.3);
const lagBlur=new LagFilter(0.2,0.4);
const lagFrame=new LagFilter(0.3,0.4);
const lagFPitch=new LagFilter(0,0.5);
const lagTStretch=new LagFilter(1,0.5);
const lagPShift=new LagFilter(0,0.5);
const lagIRLen=new LagFilter(2000,0.4);
const lagWetDry=new LagFilter(0.4,0.3);
const lagMorph=new LagFilter(0.5,0.3);
const lagXSynth=new LagFilter(0,0.3);
const lagConvPhase=new LagFilter(0,0.2);
const lagFreezeAnim=new LagFilter(0,0.15);
const lagMorphAnim=new LagFilter(0,0.2);

let mouseX=0.5,mouseY=0.5;
document.addEventListener('mousemove',e=>{mouseX=e.clientX/window.innerWidth;mouseY=e.clientY/window.innerHeight;});

// HERO WebGL
const hc=document.getElementById('hero-canvas');
hc.width=window.innerWidth;hc.height=440;
window.addEventListener('resize',()=>{hc.width=window.innerWidth;hc.height=440;initHGL();});
const HVS=`attribute vec2 pos;void main(){gl_Position=vec4(pos,0,1);}`;
const HFS=`
precision highp float;
uniform vec2 u_res;uniform float u_time;uniform vec2 u_mouse;
float hash(vec2 p){p=fract(p*vec2(127.1,311.7));p+=dot(p,p+17.5);return fract(p.x*p.y);}
float noise(vec2 p){vec2 i=floor(p),f=fract(p);vec2 u=f*f*(3.-2.*f);return mix(mix(hash(i),hash(i+vec2(1,0)),u.x),mix(hash(i+vec2(0,1)),hash(i+vec2(1)),u.x),u.y);}
float fbm(vec2 p){float v=0.,a=.5;for(int i=0;i<5;i++){v+=a*noise(p);a*=.5;p=p*2.1+vec2(1.7,9.2);}return v;}
void main(){
  vec2 uv=gl_FragCoord.xy/u_res;
  vec2 st=uv*2.-1.;st.x*=u_res.x/u_res.y;
  float t=u_time;
  // FFT bars visualization
  float bars=0.;
  for(int i=0;i<48;i++){
    float fi=float(i)/48.;
    float bx=fi*2.-1.;
    float h=0.1+0.6*pow(fbm(vec2(fi*3.+t*0.2,t*0.15)),1.5);
    float bar=step(abs(st.x-bx*u_res.x/u_res.y),.025)*step(st.y,-0.9+h*1.8);
    float colFi=float(i)/48.;
    bars+=bar*(0.4+colFi*0.6);
  }
  // Spectral energy field
  vec2 q=vec2(fbm(st*0.5+t*0.04),fbm(st*0.5+vec2(1.7,9.2)+t*0.03));
  float f=fbm(st*0.8+1.5*q+t*0.02);
  vec3 cyan=vec3(0.,0.9,1.);
  vec3 violet=vec3(0.55,0.,1.);
  vec3 col=vec3(0.01,0.005,0.04);
  vec3 barCol=mix(cyan,violet,uv.x);
  col+=barCol*bars*0.8;
  col+=mix(cyan,violet,f)*f*0.12;
  // Mouse frequency cursor
  vec2 ms=u_mouse*2.-1.;ms.x*=u_res.x/u_res.y;
  float md=abs(st.x-ms.x);
  col+=cyan*exp(-md*md*20.)*0.3;
  float vig=1.-length(uv-0.5)*1.4;
  col*=clamp(vig,0.,1.);
  col+=vec3(0.02,0.01,0.06)*sin(uv.y*200.+t)*0.03;
  gl_FragColor=vec4(col,1.);
}`;
let hgl,hprog,huniforms={};
function initHGL(){
  hgl=hc.getContext('webgl');if(!hgl)return;
  function mkS(t,src){const s=hgl.createShader(t);hgl.shaderSource(s,src);hgl.compileShader(s);return s;}
  if(hprog)hgl.deleteProgram(hprog);
  hprog=hgl.createProgram();
  hgl.attachShader(hprog,mkS(hgl.VERTEX_SHADER,HVS));
  hgl.attachShader(hprog,mkS(hgl.FRAGMENT_SHADER,HFS));
  hgl.linkProgram(hprog);hgl.useProgram(hprog);
  const buf=hgl.createBuffer();hgl.bindBuffer(hgl.ARRAY_BUFFER,buf);
  hgl.bufferData(hgl.ARRAY_BUFFER,new Float32Array([-1,-1,1,-1,-1,1,1,1]),hgl.STATIC_DRAW);
  const pl=hgl.getAttribLocation(hprog,'pos');hgl.enableVertexAttribArray(pl);hgl.vertexAttribPointer(pl,2,hgl.FLOAT,false,0,0);
  huniforms={res:hgl.getUniformLocation(hprog,'u_res'),time:hgl.getUniformLocation(hprog,'u_time'),mouse:hgl.getUniformLocation(hprog,'u_mouse')};
}
initHGL();

